Structured Dropout¶

We would like to test Structured dropout method on MNIST data, in terms of the effect on generalisation, and the effect on the correlations of the units. We will use several architectures to test the method :

  • Linear network
  • 1 hidden layer neural network with ReLu activations: in this case we test applying structured dropout on the input layer, on one hidden layer, or on both layers.
  • 2 hidden layers neural network with ReLu activations.

Models¶

While iid dropout on one layer amounts to multiply the activations of that layer by independent bernoulli variables while training, Structured dropout amounts to multiply the activations of that layer by bernoulli variables with a non-diagonal matrix. The activations of the input layer is the input data. Since sampling from multivariate bernoulli with a given covariance is known to be a difficult problem, and since multiplicative gaussian dropout works as well as dropout we sample from multivariate Gaussian using the Cholesky decompoistion (embedded in Tensorflow).

Intuition: Covariance of hidden layers units goes down during learning, so maybe decreasing it even more would result in better and faster learning. (Besides: one of the powers of representations is non-redundancy and independance (see literature in ASNI paper)) Dropout claimed to decrease correlations between units, we prove this intuition is wrong (units correlation is similar to non-dropout). When the covariance between the units decreases, in the case of iid dropout, say half of the units will be omitted (or selected) randomly and thus only the weights that will be present will see their correlations between them be reduced. In the case of structured dropout, the weights and so the bernoulli variables start by being very correlated which obliges all units to be present together and thus to have all their correlations reduced by learning.

In [3]:
from tensorflow.contrib.distributions import MultivariateNormalFullCovariance as mvnfc


def dropout_layer(x, mode, l, dim):

    if mode == 'struc':
       #mu = tf.Variable(lambda : tf.ones(shape=[dim]))
        xm = tf.reduce_mean(x, 0)
        cov = tf.matmul(tf.transpose(x-xm), x-xm) / batch_size
        cov += 1e-2 * tf.eye(dim, dtype='float32')
        sample = mvnfc(tf.zeros(shape=[dim]), cov).sample()
        return tf.multiply(x, np.sqrt(l)* sample + tf.ones(shape=[dim]))

    elif mode == 'iid_gauss':
      # mu = tf.Variable(lambda : tf.ones(shape=[dim]))
        cov =  tf.eye(dim, dtype='float32')
        sample = mvnfc(tf.zeros(shape=[dim]), cov).sample()
        return tf.multiply(x, np.sqrt(l)* sample + tf.ones(shape=[dim]))
    elif mode == 'iid_bern':
      # mu = tf.Variable(lambda : tf.ones(shape=[dim]))

#         cov =  tf.eye(dim, dtype='float32')
        p_mat = tf.constant(1/(1+l), shape=(batch_size, dim))
        sample = tf.contrib.distributions.Bernoulli(probs=p_mat, dtype='float32').sample()
        return tf.multiply( (l+1)* x, sample )
    else:  # no dropout
        return x

Now we build an MLP with 1 hidden layer. We apply dropout in three cases :

  • On both layers
  • Only on the input layer
  • Only on one of the hidden layers

We study each case separately, and plot for each case the accuracy of the resulting network on the test data and the correlation of the hidden layer unit (that is measured in terms of norm

Applying structured dropout in one layer decorrelates the units of that layer. We can see that it does decorrelate this layer as much as applying dropout on both layers.

We try a 2-hidden layer network, perform once dropout on the first hidden layer only, and second on the second hidden layer only, and a last experiment where we only apply dropout and our structured dropout on the input layer only, and check if the 2 hidden layers will be decorrelated.

nb_hidden1= 256
nb_hidden2= 10
dim=dimension

class MLP_2:

    def __init__(self, dim, nb_hidden1,nb_hidden2, nb_classes, batch_size, l, mode=None):

        self.X = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, dimension])
        self.Y = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, nb_classes])
        self.train = tf.placeholder(tf.bool)

        W1 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([dim, nb_hidden1], -0.01, 0.01))
        b1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_hidden1]))

       #self.dl1 = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.X, mode, l, dimension), lambda : self.X)
        self.dl1 = self.X
        self.err1 = self.dl1 - self.X
        self.act1 = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(self.dl1, W1) + b1)

        W2 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([nb_hidden1, nb_hidden2], -0.01, 0.01))
        b2 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_hidden2]))

        self.dl2 = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.act1, mode, l, nb_hidden1), lambda : self.act1)
        self.err2 = self.dl2 - self.act1
        self.act2 = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(self.dl2, W2) + b2)

        W3 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([nb_hidden2, nb_classes], -0.01, 0.01))
        b3 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_classes]))

        #x = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.act2, mode, l, nb_hidden2), lambda : self.act2)
        x=self.act2
        x = tf.matmul(x, W3) + b3

        # Minimize error using cross entropy
        self.probs = tf.nn.softmax(x)
        log_loss = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2(logits=x, labels=self.Y)
        self.mean_log_loss = tf.reduce_mean(log_loss)
        

def training(seqlambda, mode, max_iters=6000, learning_rate=1):

    all_accuracies = []
    all_cov_norms1 = []
    all_cov_norms2 = []
    acts1 = []
    acts2 = []

    
    for lamb in seqlambda:

        print('Lamb', lamb)
        accs = [] ; cov_norms1 = [] ;  cov_norms2 = [] ; 

        model = MLP_2(dim, nb_hidden1,nb_hidden2, nb_classes, batch_size, lamb, mode)

        # training parameters
        optimiser = tf.train.AdamOptimizer().minimize(model.mean_log_loss)

        with tf.Session() as sess:

            sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())

            for iters in range(max_iters):

                idx = np.random.randint(nb_train, size=batch_size)

                _, loss = sess.run([optimiser, model.mean_log_loss], feed_dict={
                    model.X : x_train[idx], model.Y : y_train[idx], model.train : True})
                #print(np.sum(err1))
                #print(np.sum(err2))
            

                if iters % 200 == 0:
                    print('Iteration: %d, %.03f' % (iters, loss))  
                    pred, act1,act2= sess.run([model.probs, model.act1,model.act2], 
                                    feed_dict={model.X : x_test, model.train : False})                    #print(np.sum(err1))
                    #print(np.sum(err2))
                    acc = np.sum(np.argmax(pred, axis=1) == 
                                 np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)) / float(nb_test)
                    accs.append(acc)
                    cov_norms1.append(np.linalg.norm(np.corrcoef((act1 + 1e-16 * np.random.rand(*act1.shape)).T)))
                    cov_norms2.append(np.linalg.norm(np.corrcoef((act2 + 1e-16 * np.random.rand(*act2.shape)).T)))
                    
                #    print(cov_norms1[-1])
                #    print(cov_norms2[-1])
                    print('Accuracy: %.03f' % acc)
                
            all_accuracies.append(accs)
            all_cov_norms1.append(cov_norms1)
            all_cov_norms2.append(cov_norms2)
            acts1.append(act1)
            acts2.append(act2)

    return all_accuracies, all_cov_norms1, acts1,all_cov_norms2, acts2

max_iters = 20000
lambdas = [1e-4,1e-2,1e-0]


print('#### No dropout ####')
acc_linear, cor_linear_1 , acts1_linear,cor_linear_2 , acts_linear_2 = training([None], None, max_iters)

print('#### Structured dropout ####')
acc_struc, cor_struc_1, acts1_struc, cor_struc_2 , acts_stuc_2= training(lambdas, 'struc', max_iters)

print('#### IID dropout ####')
acc_iid,cor_iid_1, acts1_iid, cor_iid_2 , acts_iid_2= training(lambdas, 'iid_gauss', max_iters)

print('#### IID bern dropout ####')
acc_iid_bern,cor_iid_1_bern, acts1_iid_bern, cor_iid_2_bern , acts_iid_2_bern = training(lambdas, 'iid_bern', max_iters)

sns.reset_orig()
max_iters=20000

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))

ax.plot(np.arange(200, max_iters, 200), acc_linear[0][1:] , linestyle='-.',
        linewidth=1, color='red', label='accuracy')

ax.legend(loc=1, prop={'size': 15})

ax2 = ax.twinx()

ax2.plot(np.arange(200, max_iters, 200),  cor_linear_1[0][1:] , linestyle='-.',
        linewidth=1, color='green', label='1st hidden layer correlation')

ax2.plot(np.arange(200, max_iters, 200),  cor_linear_2[0][1:] , linestyle='-.',
        linewidth=1, color='blue', label='2nd hidden layer correlation')


ax.set_xlabel('iteration')
ax.set_ylabel('$|\cdot|_F$')

#ax.set_ylim([0.8, 1.0])

ax2.legend(loc=7, prop={'size': 15})
plt.show()


















































It is interesting here to note that structured dropout decorrelates both hidden layers, however it does decorrelate the second hidden layer activations, where it is applied, more than it did when applied on the first hidden layer, and it does decorrelate the first hidden layer less than when it was applied only on this layer.


Note here that : we didn't look for the best parameter value for accuracy, see the previous markdowns and the paper for the best accuracy comparaison.


We can conlcude that: if one wants only to have decorrelated representations on one or several layers (which will be generally the last layers of the networks), structured dropout can be applied only on those layers. 
If one want to improve generalisation, structured dropout may be useful for all layers and several dropout rates should be searched. We showed in the ASNI report that moderately small values of $\lambda$ work well. 
There remains many questions in this line of work.

















We are not saying that there is a causal link between correlations of the hidden layers and accuracy, but the same dynamics are happening by the optimisation proccess that one can try to enhance its effect on the decorrelation hoping that it will also have an effect on the accuracy

nb_hidden1= 256
nb_hidden2= 128
dim=dimension
class MLP_2:

    def __init__(self, dim, nb_hidden1,nb_hidden2, nb_classes, batch_size, l, mode=None):

        self.X = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, dimension])
        self.Y = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, nb_classes])
        self.train = tf.placeholder(tf.bool)

        W1 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([dim, nb_hidden1], -0.01, 0.01))
        b1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_hidden1]))

        self.dl1 = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.X, mode, l, dimension), lambda : self.X)        
        self.err1 = self.dl1 - self.X
        self.act1 = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(self.dl1, W1) + b1)

        W2 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([nb_hidden1, nb_hidden2], -0.01, 0.01))
        b2 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_hidden2]))

        #self.dl2 = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.act1, mode, l, nb_hidden1), lambda : self.act1)
        self.dl2=self.act1
        self.err2 = self.dl2 - self.act1
        self.act2 = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(self.dl2, W2) + b2)

        W3 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([nb_hidden2, nb_classes], -0.01, 0.01))
        b3 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_classes]))

        #x = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.act2, mode, l, nb_hidden2), lambda : self.act2)
        x=self.act2
        x = tf.matmul(x, W3) + b3

        # Minimize error using cross entropy
        self.probs = tf.nn.softmax(x)
        log_loss = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2(logits=x, labels=self.Y)
        self.mean_log_loss = tf.reduce_mean(log_loss)

nb_hidden1= 256
nb_hidden2= 128
dim=dimension
class MLP_2:

    def __init__(self, dim, nb_hidden1,nb_hidden2, nb_classes, batch_size, l, mode=None):

        self.X = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, dimension])
        self.Y = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, nb_classes])
        self.train = tf.placeholder(tf.bool)

        W1 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([dim, nb_hidden1], -0.01, 0.01))
        b1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_hidden1]))

        self.dl1 = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.X, mode, l, dimension), lambda : self.X)        
        self.err1 = self.dl1 - self.X
        self.act1 = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(self.dl1, W1) + b1)

        W2 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([nb_hidden1, nb_hidden2], -0.01, 0.01))
        b2 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_hidden2]))

        self.dl2 = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.act1, mode, l, nb_hidden1), lambda : self.act1)
        #self.dl2=self.act1
        self.err2 = self.dl2 - self.act1
        self.act2 = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(self.dl2, W2) + b2)

        W3 = tf.Variable(tf.random_uniform([nb_hidden2, nb_classes], -0.01, 0.01))
        b3 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(shape=[nb_classes]))

        x = tf.cond(self.train, lambda : dropout_layer(self.act2, mode, l, nb_hidden2), lambda : self.act2)
        #x=self.act2
        x = tf.matmul(x, W3) + b3

        # Minimize error using cross entropy
        self.probs = tf.nn.softmax(x)
        log_loss = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2(logits=x, labels=self.Y)
        self.mean_log_loss = tf.reduce_mean(log_loss)
